  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Ancient Foundation of Yengyong Palace
  author: Sung Hyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Gogryeong ridge rises to pierce the void, its traces floating in purple and green.
    The dragon coils, the tiger crouches—they cradle the sacred realm.
    Above the Kangahn Hall, a thousand pines stand sentinel.
    Before the Weibong Tower, but a single mound of earth remains.
    The fragrance of silken robes has vanished; only spring lingers on.
    The pipes and songs have ceased their chorus; only water flows indifferent.
    Why inquire into the rise and fall of empires?
    At day's end, wind and mist fill the eye—and fill the heart with sorrow.
  footnotes:
    - Gogryeong ridge and the directional imagery (dragon and tiger) evoke the geomantic principles that once guided the palace's placement, now rendered meaningless by its decay.
    - Kangahn Hall and Weibong Tower were structures within Yengyong Palace, now reduced to earthen mounds—a poignant image of temporal impermanence.
    - 'The final couplet reflects the Buddhist-influenced philosophical stance common to Korean literati poetry: acceptance that the rise and fall of human institutions is inevitable and not worth lamenting.'
